h3. Summary
Stash does not use outbound proxy to connect to Marketplace

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Add the following into {{setenv.h}}
{noformat}
JVM_SUPPORT_RECOMMENDED_ARGS="-Dhttp.proxyHost=<proxy.host> -Dhttp.proxyPort=<proxy_port>"
{noformat}
# Restart Stash
# Access {{Administration >> Add-ons >> Manage add-ons}}

h3. Expected Results
Stash should be using the outbound proxy server to access Marketplace

h3. Actual Results
Stash accessing Marketplace without going through the outbound proxy server

Currently spaces must be manually percent-encoded for the Markdown to be recognized as an image link.

E.g.

{code}![this is required](images/fo%20o.png){code}

not

{code}![this is required](images/fo o.png){code}

A link like

{noformat}
[test](mailto:x@x.com)
{noformat}

Doesn't work in Markdown. A link is created, but points nowhere. A link like:

{noformat}
[test](mailto:x@x.com;y@y.com?subject=test)
{noformat}

Isn't even parsed correctly and doesn't turn into a link.

Stash does not indicate that a request for metadata timed out in the REST response. Instead, if the request reaches the timeout, that information is excluded from the response.

The response should indicate that the metadata was attempted to be loaded, but reached the timeout.

For example, requests to {{/rest/api/1.0/projects/PROJ/repos/repo/branches?details=true}} should include the ahead/behind information from {{com.atlassian.stash.stash-branch-utils:ahead-behind-metadata-provider}}. If this metadata takes too long, it's not included in the response. 

{code}...
"metadata": {
        "com.atlassian.stash.stash-branch-utils:latest-changeset-metadata": {
          "id": "dc82ee974d8dd56ea441a76e661daec3fec0b498",
          "displayId": "dc82ee974d8",
          "author": {
            "name": "Jeff Thomas",
            "emailAddress": "",
            "avatarUrl": ""
          },
          "authorTimestamp": 1429562672000,
          "message": "Adding file to test",
          "parents": [
            {
              "id": "42cf7864604b569017bc64dab1609653293c4f39",
              "displayId": "42cf7864604"
            }
          ]
        }
      }
...{code}

Currently, it is not possible to {{go get}} a sub-package, i.e. {{go get <stash>/<project>/<repo>/<sub>/<directory>}}.

Changes required:
# loosen the URL requirement for the import path (from {{<stash>/<project>/<repo>}} to {{<stash>/<project>/<repo>(/<directory>)*}}
# assume everything after {{<repo>}} is a sub-directory path
# return *the same meta tag* that would get returned for just {{go get <stash>/<project>/<repo>}}

What {{go get}} will do is hit the {{http://<stash>/<project>/<repo>/<sub>/<directory>}} page looking for the {{go-import}} meta-tag, find a tag with a import _prefix_ for the whole repository, hit the prefixed page {{http://<stash>/<project>/<repo>}}, find the original meta-tag, check out the repository, and install the requested package.

While reviewing a pull request, I noticed that when I hover the mouse over the [Approve] button in the upper right corner of the web page, it displays the following tool tip text:

{noformat}
  Approve this pull request (Type 'a')
{noformat}

Nice to have a hot key to approve!

I would first recommend lowercasing "Type"; as a result, the tool tip text would read as follows:

{noformat}
  Approve this pull request (type 'a')
{noformat}

When I hover the mouse over the [Approve] button after having approved the pull request, the tool tip text now reads as follows:

{noformat}
  You have approved this pull request (Type 'a')
{noformat}

At first, I was going to recommend removing the text "(Type 'a')" from the end of the tool tip text (since I had already approved the pull request) but then realized that this is a way to unapprove (undo the approval).

In response, therefore, I recommend replacing the text in this scenario with:

{noformat}
  You have approved this pull request (type 'a' to unapprove)
{noformat}

or:

{noformat}
  You have approved this pull request (type 'a' to undo the approval)
{noformat}

or some other wording that elucidates that typing 'a' undoes the current state.

If I create a new repository on Stash, Stash suggests the following command for an existing git repo:

{code}
cd existing-project
git remote set-url origin http://my-stash-host/scm/test/stash_branching_test.git
git push origin master
{code}

However, this assumes that my git repo has already has a remote called 'origin'. If not, a user following these instructions will get the following error:

{code}
git remote set-url origin http://my-stash-host/scm/bar/foo.git
fatal: No such remote 'origin'
{code}

I think the common case is having a git repo without a remote called 'origin'. Users typically have imported code from somewhere else or have created a brand new repo, meaning they don't have an 'origin'. If a user already had 'origin' set up, they may not need Stash!

I suggest changing the instructions to:

{code}
cd existing-project
git remote add origin http://my-stash-host/scm/bar/foo.git
git push origin master
{code}

This should work in more cases, and I think the failure case (already having an 'origin') is more explicit:

{code}
git remote add origin http://my-stash-host/scm/bar/foo.git
fatal: remote origin already exists.
{code}
